    "user_reviews": [
      {
        "title": "Stage one remap for 9950x",
        "text": "This was bought to replace my 9950x, which was a reliable replacement for the nightmare that was a 7950x3d with scheduling issues in the early days. Two years later and Windows and AMD have long sorted those out. How to describe the difference between the 9950x and this 9950x3d2?\nFor those that like to tune their car, as the title says it's a stage one remap for the 9950x. It doesn't seem to go any faster at the top end, but it gets there hella lot easier. If you have already bought a discounted 9950x3d, bargain and keep it, the upgrade will not be worth it.\nIt's early days yet but temperatues are ever so slightly better than the 9950x just a degree or 2 at idle, benchmarking it scored around the same but maybe 4 to 5 degrees cooler. I'm running negative 15 all cores, the 9950 x seemed to like all core negative 10 in curve optimiser. Each to their own I guess.\nAs this review is really early after installation there'll be loads to try out yet. Okay I just wanted the first review LOL, but for me how responsive my system has just become, I'm happy with the remap. Now just need to sell the 9950x and remap the car..........................",
        "source": "overclockers.co.uk",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "2 months ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK2caRtLOuLToXstjBAIbQkKyLEbgwkvuSO8cbBV7DTq3zsL_nGmco2-v7c7qJDRwUG6bw=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc"
      },
      {
        "title": "The king of CPU's",
        "text": "This monster can do it all and it performs flawlessly, I think the negative reviews this CPU has received isn't fair as it's still the best CPU available. Just make sure you've got adequate cooling.",
        "source": "overclockers.co.uk",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "2 months ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK2caRtLOuLToXstjBAIbQkKyLEbgwkvuSO8cbBV7DTq3zsL_nGmco2-v7c7qJDRwUG6bw=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc"
      },
      {
        "title": "Worth price in more use cases than reviewers admit",
        "text": "The down and dirty is that if your build is 100% for gaming, buying this CPU is merely a flex. However, the more heavily your workload includes productivity, the more this CPU makes sense and is worth every penny. In other words, if you use your machine for earning income, it's a no-brainer. I actually started my July 2025 build with the 9950X3D and upgraded to this on launch. There is a noticeable improvement when running multiple platforms simultaneously, as it eliminates all the Windows scheduling issues. If your decision rests solely on the benchmarking \"numbers\" reported by various content creators who are advising against this CPU for \"value\" reasons, you might miss out on an opportunity to get through heavy workloads faster. The people who need this CPU will make up the price difference very quickly through increased efficiency.",
